"The great and powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language.
While lawmakers and civil rights activists are debating the usefulness of the law on compulsory language tests for immigrants, criminals are already acting with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the upkeep of the remaining families in the country.
On December 1, a law in force, according to which each working immigrant must pass a test, certified the knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the local housing industry and retail.
However, the tests over time, according to the migration agency transformed in the future for all guest workers will be on duty.
At the same time, we must not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the foundations of the legislation.
Language skills are both for the preservation and the extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also, with the exception of this law, people who received their education certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
